To make a wish one threw into the water a small metal object, like a pin or coin. Many bubbles arising from it meant a rapid granting of one's wish, few bubbles meant a long period of time would elapse before it came true. No bubbles meant that the wish had not been granted
It’s what’s known as a clootie well, where token offerings are placed around and within the well, and strips of cloth and ribbons are hung from neighbouring trees. It's also used as a wishing well.

Local tradition is that it is the only one remaining of originally nine holy wells  in Trellech. In the 17th century, it was reportedly much frequented, and reputed to cure ‘the scurvy, colic and other distempers’.

The well in A Reckless Match is based on the real-life Virtuous Well, sometimes known as St Anne’s Well, a circular wellspring located in a field on the left of the road to Tintern, about 400 yards east of the village of Trellech. https://t.co/KcblnsNu2M
